<div id="review_3849420483" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3849420483" />
    <a title="Beth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15888260-beth"><img alt="Beth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1459714355p2/15888260.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3849420483?book_show_action=true">Mar 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beth" href="/user/show/15888260-beth">Beth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780316739115" href="/book/show/2901735-sudden-sea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3849420483" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3928004854775108075">I&apos;m torn between 3.5 and 4*; going with four based on comparable other reviews of mine.<br/>This book came recommended and is proof that we each read our own story.<br/>There is an early reference to Cotton and Increase Mather. Why do I mention this? I happened to have a high school teacher named Brian Mather who was a descendent of this family. <br/>Similarly in attempting to describe the hurricane&apos;s strength, it was noted that before it blew, the anemometer at the Blue Hill Observatory in Milton, MA, some se</span>
  <span id="freeText3928004854775108075" style="display:none">I'm torn between 3.5 and 4*; going with four based on comparable other reviews of mine.<br />This book came recommended and is proof that we each read our own story.<br />There is an early reference to Cotton and Increase Mather. Why do I mention this? I happened to have a high school teacher named Brian Mather who was a descendent of this family. <br />Similarly in attempting to describe the hurricane's strength, it was noted that before it blew, the anemometer at the Blue Hill Observatory in Milton, MA, some seventy miles from the eye of the storm, recorded gusts of 186 MPH and a sustained wind speed of 121 MPH. It was the 2nd highest rate ever recorded in the Northern Hemisphere. My attention was drawn to this due to a college friend being from Milton. <br /><br />Back to the basics of the book. A few shortcomings for me. There was some detail I skimmed because there were, overall, a lot of facts. Also, many people were introduced at the beginning of the book, but luckily in a few early pages, making it easy for me to refer back later when they were again mentioned.<br /><br />The author has some lovely writing, use of words and phrases, and interesting facts. Here are some samples: <br />*** My favorite line: Their favorite sport was one-upmanship.<br />*** Another: In those days, lighting a woman's cigarette was tantamount to an act of seduction. If she inhaled, you could book a room with a private bath and radio at the Hotel Taft in NYC for $2.50!<br />*** The Great Hurricane of 1938 made landfall at Patchogue, LI, striking with such force that is set off seismographs in Alaska. <br />*** What the eye saw, the mind could not process and the heart refused to accept.<br />*** Charles Pierce, the only forecaster to recognize the danger, received a promotion and was moved to the analysis division. He remained with the Weather Bureau (now the Nat'l Weather Service) for the rest of his career!<br />*** The week after the hurricane was the busiest ever in airline travel in the US.<br />Lastly, we get to some observations that remind me of things that could be said about COVID-19. This is interesting given the book was written in 2003.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3928004854775108075" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


