    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3503752996" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3503752996" />
    <a title="Justin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3248359-justin"><img alt="Justin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360894967p2/3248359.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3503752996?book_show_action=true">Aug 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Justin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Justin" rel="nofollow" href="/user/show/3248359-justin">Justin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3503752996" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer185368493793877784">3.5/5 This was a decent book about a hurricane that I knew little about. Breaking conventional wisdom and all expectations, a massive hurricane swept past Florida, and instead of curling out to sea, shot straight north towards Long Island. Because storm trackers communicated with each other primarily in their own regions, no one told New England that this enormous, fast moving storm was on its way. Picnickers scouted out to the barrier islands surrounding Narragansett Bay in Rhode Island, one mo</span>
  <span id="freeText185368493793877784" style="display:none">3.5/5 This was a decent book about a hurricane that I knew little about. Breaking conventional wisdom and all expectations, a massive hurricane swept past Florida, and instead of curling out to sea, shot straight north towards Long Island. Because storm trackers communicated with each other primarily in their own regions, no one told New England that this enormous, fast moving storm was on its way. Picnickers scouted out to the barrier islands surrounding Narragansett Bay in Rhode Island, one moment enjoying the warm September weather, and the next fighting for their lives as a 30 foot storm surge leveled towns and communities along the New England coast. The author does a decent job capturing the lives and stories of those who witnessed the storm of 1938, but at times the narrative is bumbling. There are somewhat failed attempts to weave in disconnected storylines such as Catherine Hepburn’s relationship with Howard Hughes (it’s barely relevant), and the organization isn’t great, nor is the explanation of the science. Erik Larson’s “Isaac’s Storm” does much better on both counts. Strangely, now that I’ve read both of these books (Isaac’s Storm is about the hurricane that struck Galveston Texas in 1900), I find it odd that neither narrative references the other, as if we find it preferable not to correlate these seemingly random acts of god.</span>
  <a data-text-id="185368493793877784" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

